WEBVTT

00:27.680 --> 00:27.880
Sottotitoli creati dalla comunità Amara.org

00:30.660 --> 00:33.000
Se vi sedete...

00:39.060 --> 00:41.960
Ci sono molte altre persone in l'altra parte della città.

00:42.100 --> 00:44.220
Quando sono arrivato, ho detto, come si fa?

00:44.580 --> 00:45.860
Ci sono molte persone.

00:46.800 --> 00:49.100
Tutti erano in città per un caffè.

00:49.480 --> 00:50.640
Per un caffè.

00:51.980 --> 00:53.340
Parla con...

00:53.340 --> 00:54.380
Come si chiama questo?

00:55.320 --> 00:56.680
Sì, si, ci ha parlato.

00:56.680 --> 01:00.780
L'altro ha detto, ok, fai, è un'excellente idea.

01:02.080 --> 01:07.160
E lui ha detto la tua idea di un citto di conferenze.

01:07.420 --> 01:11.960
Naturalmente dobbiamo identificare i temi che siano in qualche...

01:11.960 --> 01:14.920
Ma avere uno sponsor come Laboi non sarebbe una cosa...

01:15.520 --> 01:19.440
Cominciando ad avere questi sponsor.

01:21.200 --> 01:25.700
Ormai le compagnie aeree sono meglio delle banche, che è tutto dire.

01:26.580 --> 01:28.800
Le banche sono un vero disastro.

01:28.860 --> 01:30.660
Veramente, chi l'avrebbe mai pensato?

01:30.660 --> 01:32.700
Chi l'avrebbe mai pensato?

01:35.180 --> 01:38.520
Sì, per l'Italia è un problema, perché il grosso del non profit

01:38.520 --> 01:43.660
è tutto delle fondazioni che infatti io ho con i profitti del banco.

01:44.020 --> 01:48.240
Se i profitti del banco scendono, tutto il non profit in Italia si trasconde.

01:48.420 --> 01:49.020
Sparisce?

01:50.200 --> 01:51.320
Questo è grave?

01:51.560 --> 01:52.140
Sì.

01:53.040 --> 01:55.500
Io parlo diversi.

01:55.540 --> 01:55.980
Ok?

01:55.980 --> 02:00.980
Il seguimento progressivo alle realtà che emergono nel panorama internazionale

02:00.980 --> 02:06.420
e che sono rese ancora più importanti e delicate e complesse

02:06.420 --> 02:11.540
dalla crisi economica e finanziaria nella quale il mondo si trova oggi.

02:12.540 --> 02:17.640
Quindi questi sono gli assi della politica estera italiana,

02:17.820 --> 02:19.440
riassunti molto brevemente,

02:19.440 --> 02:24.560
che noi pensiamo di poter continuare a mettere a disposizione

02:24.560 --> 02:26.220
della nuova amministrazione americana,

02:26.280 --> 02:30.440
come, ripeto, abbiamo fatto nel passato con tutte le amministrazioni

02:30.980 --> 02:35.220
del nostro amico ed alleato transatlantico.

02:35.620 --> 02:40.640
Non ho certamente definito un'agenda del nuovo presidente americano,

02:40.920 --> 02:45.120
ho cercato di definire l'agenda di politica estera dell'Italia.

02:45.120 --> 02:51.220
Ma l'importante è che queste agende siano sempre più concordanti fra di loro

02:51.220 --> 02:56.380
e sempre più indirizzate verso il conseguimento di risposte comuni

02:56.740 --> 02:58.240
alle sfide che ci fronteggiano.

02:58.460 --> 02:59.540
Vi ringrazio.

03:04.760 --> 03:10.160
Bene, io ringrazio i nostri amici e le istituzioni che esse rappresentano.

03:10.540 --> 03:12.540
Ora passiamo al primo panel.

03:12.540 --> 03:18.880
Io mi trattengo, ma anche tu sei padrone di casa.

03:19.020 --> 03:19.740
Ciao, stavi bene.

03:27.300 --> 03:29.860
Allora, Michael e John.

03:34.920 --> 03:38.720
Questo è l'unico bicchiere che se ne va, questi sono tutti a posto.

03:38.720 --> 03:43.720
We have too many chairs now.

03:49.120 --> 03:50.880
Abbiamo troppi segni.

03:50.880 --> 03:52.480
I'm John Hart, my friend.

04:38.640 --> 04:40.040
Ok.

04:50.880 --> 04:53.660
Ok, we switch to English now,

04:54.460 --> 04:58.240
because we have two American speakers.

04:59.240 --> 05:03.600
There is, I suppose, a simultaneous translation for those who need it.

05:05.600 --> 05:10.240
And therefore, the new president's foreign policy agenda,

05:11.980 --> 05:21.040
which will somehow be the thread of our entire day of panels and discussions.

05:22.420 --> 05:25.340
We begin with two wonderful speakers.

05:25.640 --> 05:28.140
I don't know whether you are familiar with them.

05:28.980 --> 05:34.160
Michael Lind is a very sort of extravagant expert in these matters.

05:34.910 --> 05:43.120
I like him also because he has published poetry and a book for children.

05:44.240 --> 05:45.820
I like very much the idea.

05:46.220 --> 05:50.560
I did it myself, but it was not supposed to be published.

05:50.720 --> 05:55.080
It was just written and it was published also.

05:56.180 --> 05:58.460
Not so successful as yours.

05:59.180 --> 06:01.080
But I mean, it was nice anyhow.

06:02.940 --> 06:06.080
I don't think the initiative for this will come from Obama himself.

06:06.240 --> 06:09.680
If you look at the people, the economic advisors he has surrounded himself with,

06:09.860 --> 06:12.140
they are quite centrist traditional people.

06:12.560 --> 06:15.760
Paul Volcker, for example, and not to mention Larry Summers.

06:16.020 --> 06:18.300
But there's going to be strong pressure within Congress,

06:19.260 --> 06:20.420
within the Democratic Congress,

06:21.040 --> 06:23.620
and within various constituencies of the Democratic Party

06:23.620 --> 06:25.380
to change the liberal rules of the game,

06:25.440 --> 06:27.920
which many feel have penalized the United States.

06:29.500 --> 06:31.840
To conclude, and for the sake of argument,

06:32.440 --> 06:34.560
and since there hasn't been much good news recently,

06:34.660 --> 06:36.620
let me give you a few reasons to be optimistic

06:37.440 --> 06:40.620
about the future of U.S.-European relations at least.

06:42.760 --> 06:47.240
The first is that the worst of the war on terror and Iraq effect

06:47.240 --> 06:49.280
on transatlantic relations is over.

06:50.240 --> 06:53.860
Obama's election has already had a positive effect

06:53.860 --> 06:56.700
on the European view of the United States.

06:56.700 --> 06:59.000
And if the U.S. plays its cards right,

06:59.160 --> 07:02.620
this improvement can continue for the next four years.

07:03.860 --> 07:07.500
Intellectual clichés like America as Mars and Europe as Venus

07:07.500 --> 07:10.300
have been discredited, in particular in the U.S.,

07:10.300 --> 07:11.960
where they were once taken seriously.

07:13.140 --> 07:15.560
The latest cliché, the return of history,

07:15.660 --> 07:19.900
that the future will look like the 19th century great power conflict,

07:20.360 --> 07:21.720
I think is also misleading,

07:21.820 --> 07:25.040
and I hope that believing it does not become a self-fulfilling prophecy.

07:27.080 --> 07:30.840
Although some argue that U.S. and European values

07:30.840 --> 07:33.820
and social models are diverging,

07:34.240 --> 07:39.060
there has now been a convergence in terms of regulation,

07:39.820 --> 07:41.660
regulatory and financial questions.

07:42.580 --> 07:46.520
I think that the big economic and strategic interests of Europe

07:46.520 --> 07:47.760
are still similar.

07:48.340 --> 07:50.520
I think the elites on both sides of the Atlantic

07:50.520 --> 07:54.260
basically recognize this, that we are in the same boat.

07:55.980 --> 08:00.620
I think it's even possible that in light of their recent military

08:00.620 --> 08:05.780
and financial failures, the U.S. elites,

08:05.900 --> 08:07.320
I was going to say comeuppances,

08:07.460 --> 08:10.440
but I doubt if the translator would have a word for that.

08:10.580 --> 08:11.880
How do you say that in Italian?

08:12.760 --> 08:13.240
Comeuppance.

08:13.740 --> 08:16.600
In light of their recent military and financial failures,

08:17.180 --> 08:20.320
the U.S. elites may even be ready to take more seriously

08:20.320 --> 08:22.480
than they have in recent decades their own rhetoric

08:22.480 --> 08:24.920
about the idea of an equal partnership,

08:24.980 --> 08:27.640
which goes back to the Kennedy and Truman

08:28.440 --> 08:30.780
and Eisenhower administrations.

08:31.040 --> 08:36.240
In other words, perhaps something resembling an equal partnership

08:36.240 --> 08:40.800
between Europe and America is an idea whose time has finally come.

08:41.380 --> 08:42.160
Thank you.

08:42.160 --> 08:43.120
Very good.

08:50.280 --> 08:54.900
So even though there was no previous agreement between the two of you,

08:54.920 --> 08:58.700
there was a reason for having Michael Lin speaking first

08:58.700 --> 09:03.360
and you speaking second, because he said to us where we are now,

09:04.120 --> 09:09.440
and after him you said to us where President Obama can go from here

09:09.440 --> 09:13.720
and where all of us can go from here, somewhere else.

09:14.200 --> 09:17.080
We have just understood that we have to go somewhere else,

09:17.120 --> 09:21.740
but not exactly where to, which is already something.

09:22.580 --> 09:30.440
Having said so, now it's already 11.30 and the second panel should begin now.

09:32.020 --> 09:37.460
Okay, but we are entitled to some more minutes because we begin later.

09:37.460 --> 09:43.440
Let me take with your permission, which is not very democratic,

09:43.620 --> 09:46.600
this is the typical case of guided democracy,

09:49.380 --> 09:54.860
let me state at the beginning that we will take three questions,

09:55.160 --> 10:02.660
no more than three, and therefore please the three one after the other

10:02.660 --> 10:07.920
and you will respond to all of them in order to...

10:07.920 --> 10:14.400
So, Madame, you are the first one, I have a second here and a third there,

10:14.460 --> 10:15.480
and that's all.

10:16.400 --> 10:20.840
Guided democracy has some sort of cost.

10:26.420 --> 10:30.660
I read a very interesting article by Michael Adhett in the Time International

10:31.420 --> 10:35.700
and it said it's time that America realized that you have to cooperate

10:35.700 --> 10:37.980
and work with the rest of the world.

10:39.480 --> 10:43.300
The ambassador said you have to contain the al-Qaeda.

10:44.260 --> 10:50.400
Obama in his election speech said that he wanted to talk to Taliban in Afghanistan.

10:51.300 --> 10:58.320
Maybe a lot of, rather the impositions and talking helps out in a lot of things.

10:58.320 --> 11:06.740
Do you think that the Obama administration will talk to Taliban to solve the problems?

11:06.760 --> 11:11.320
This happened in Iraq because they engaged the Sunni administration

11:11.840 --> 11:14.420
and then they had the peace talks afterwards.

11:23.680 --> 11:26.020
Thank you for your presentations.

11:26.020 --> 11:30.980
My question refers to the background that you made during your presentations.

11:31.920 --> 11:36.660
There is the three realities which were made by John Harper,

11:38.680 --> 11:41.600
the three realities of the current US administration,

11:42.620 --> 11:45.180
and the war of choice, the war of necessity.

11:46.000 --> 11:51.880
Which will be the US policy toward long lasting conflicts in Africa,

11:51.880 --> 11:57.740
I mean like Darfur, which has the potential to spill over, or it has already done.

11:59.340 --> 11:59.880
Thank you.

12:00.340 --> 12:06.580
Thank you both, it was a very good start.

12:07.400 --> 12:12.060
Michael, very quickly, I agree with you that strategically integrating the BRICS

12:12.060 --> 12:16.340
into a Euro-Atlantic norms-based system is the strategic challenge for the next 30 years.

12:16.360 --> 12:17.080
That's the game.

12:17.400 --> 12:21.140
Can we create a new order where they are status quo players and not revolutionary players?

12:21.140 --> 12:23.820
Do you have any ideas practically on how that can be done?

12:23.980 --> 12:28.480
Because to me that is the overriding question and the rest of this to some extent is flummery.

12:29.220 --> 12:32.380
Mr. Harper, the point that kept striking me as you were talking is

12:32.380 --> 12:33.940
not that you're wrong about American comeuppance,

12:34.000 --> 12:36.720
but no notion of European weakness in this.

12:37.900 --> 12:39.720
We are both in relative decline.

12:41.140 --> 12:44.440
Europe may be in a steeper decline, you can certainly argue that.

12:44.720 --> 12:47.320
How do you set up a partnership when that's the situation?

12:47.420 --> 12:49.360
You only looked at the problems that America had

12:49.360 --> 12:51.260
without looking at the problems Europe has,

12:51.420 --> 12:53.600
which is contextually going to be part of this bargain

12:53.600 --> 12:55.580
that you rightly talk about needs to be made.

12:55.680 --> 12:58.760
But to ignore that is not to be able to make that bargain.

13:00.000 --> 13:02.540
It's not very encouraging, that's the notion.

13:04.420 --> 13:06.800
Okay, so you now have the minute.

13:08.140 --> 13:10.900
Well, brief answers to the three questions.

13:11.420 --> 13:13.880
With respect to talking to the Taliban,

13:14.760 --> 13:18.880
it's my understanding that the US military would like to repeat

13:18.880 --> 13:21.160
what went on with the Anbar Awakening,

13:21.400 --> 13:25.760
that is a matter of diplomacy and of psychological warfare

13:25.760 --> 13:30.560
to separate Al-Qaeda from some of its allies,

13:31.100 --> 13:33.700
particularly among the Pashtuns in Afghanistan.

13:34.400 --> 13:38.840
If you look at how terrorist movements are defeated,

13:39.640 --> 13:44.220
it often comes from the separation of those with purely political motives

13:44.220 --> 13:47.040
who think that the militant aspects are counterproductive

13:47.040 --> 13:49.400
from the die-hard militants.

13:49.740 --> 13:51.340
So that would seem promising.

13:51.580 --> 13:55.940
I'm sure the United States will not have any negotiations with Al-Qaeda,

13:56.240 --> 13:58.720
but if they can separate Al-Qaeda from some of its allies,

13:58.760 --> 14:01.720
then I think everyone would agree that that's a promising strategy.

14:02.160 --> 14:06.480
With respect to Darfur, if my analysis of US public opinion is correct,

14:06.820 --> 14:10.460
as well as Professor Harper's correct emphasis

14:10.460 --> 14:13.180
on the fiscal constraints of the US military,

14:13.180 --> 14:18.000
I believe that the cost of US interventions in Iraq and Afghanistan

14:18.000 --> 14:23.000
have pretty much eliminated the likelihood of large-scale humanitarian interventions.

14:23.140 --> 14:25.200
That's not to say you can't do something on a small scale,

14:25.460 --> 14:26.980
particularly with allied help,

14:27.620 --> 14:32.620
but I don't foresee any major humanitarian interventions

14:32.620 --> 14:36.000
involving the US military in the next few years.

14:36.560 --> 14:41.380
And finally, integrating developing countries like China, India and Brazil

14:41.380 --> 14:45.340
into a new system of status quo powers.

14:46.080 --> 14:47.380
I think that can be done,

14:47.880 --> 14:54.560
but only if the new multilateral economic order is results-based rather than rule-based.

14:55.100 --> 14:55.820
Let me repeat that.

14:55.840 --> 14:58.240
It needs to be results-based rather than rule-based.

14:58.540 --> 15:01.880
These are countries at different stages of industrial and financial development,

15:02.160 --> 15:03.600
and they have conflicting interests.

15:04.080 --> 15:06.680
I think the United States and some of its allies

15:06.680 --> 15:10.580
prematurely wanted a global agreement

15:10.580 --> 15:13.460
on international economic rules and regulation

15:13.460 --> 15:18.840
that took the form of adherence to laws and law-like regulations.

15:20.560 --> 15:23.480
I would just recommend a return to diplomacy.

15:23.720 --> 15:27.380
That is, in areas of trade and finance, everything is negotiable,

15:27.660 --> 15:33.060
and it's not a matter of settling on one system of universal rules once and for all.

15:34.220 --> 15:37.960
That's an idea, based on results and not on rules.

15:39.680 --> 15:42.100
I don't know how we can do it, but anyhow.

15:44.060 --> 15:44.620
Yes, please.

15:44.680 --> 15:49.200
Okay, I think on Afghanistan, I think I agree with what was just said.

15:49.500 --> 15:55.060
I think that probably Petraeus's inclination will be to try to split the,

15:55.780 --> 16:00.300
call them the viable elements of the insurgency,

16:00.300 --> 16:03.020
as he did with the awakening councils in Iraq.

16:03.580 --> 16:06.120
I think that's the right approach to take.

16:06.260 --> 16:09.100
You have to try to split those who will be bought off

16:09.100 --> 16:11.140
and will be integrated into the system,

16:11.200 --> 16:14.400
and who are angry because their families and clansmen have been killed,

16:14.420 --> 16:17.640
as opposed to those who are hardcore al-Qaeda.

16:18.080 --> 16:19.320
You have to split the two.

16:19.540 --> 16:23.660
There's a very good article by Barnett Rubin in The Current Foreign Affairs,

16:24.100 --> 16:25.580
where he talks about this.

16:25.620 --> 16:29.060
He also talks about the problem of Pakistan, which most of us ignore,

16:29.060 --> 16:31.920
probably because it's so complicated, we can't understand it.

16:32.120 --> 16:36.040
Something has to be done to reassure the Pakistanis that the Afghani...

